INSERT INTO `counters` VALUES (1,'Mewtwo','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/7/78/150Mewtwo.png',150,'Cresselia','Confusion','Psychic','Shadow Ball','Ghost','An all around great counter if you have the coveted legacy move, Shadow Ball. Mewtwo has the well rounded stats to make it a great generalist and a hard hitter against Cresselia',2),(2,'Giratina (Origin)','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/2/2b/487Giratina-Origin.png',487,'Cresselia','Shadow Claw','Ghost','Shadow Ball','Ghost','Origin Form Giratina is the best when it comes to fighting Cresselia. Its impressive bulk and high attack allow it to survive in battle much longer than glass cannons like Gengar',1),(4,'Gengar','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/c/c6/094Gengar.png',94,'Cresselia','Shadow Claw/Lick','Ghost','Shadow Ball','Ghost','The super fast, super powerful glass cannon makes a return to the raid meta scene as one of the highest DPS counters for Cresselia. However, only use Gengar if you have the coveted fast move Shadow Claw, or its Raid Day exclusive move Lick.',3),(5,'Giratina (Origin)','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/2/2b/487Giratina-Origin.png',487,'Deoxys (Def)','Shadow Claw','Ghost','Shadow Ball','Ghost','If it\'s weak to Ghost, your best bet will be Giratina Origin. Shadow Claw/Shadow Ball makes Giratina Origin like a bulky Gengar. It is the supreme Ghost type counter.',1),(6,'Gengar','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/c/c6/094Gengar.png',94,'Deoxys (Def)','Shadow Claw/Lick','Ghost','Shadow Ball','Ghost','If it\'s weak to Ghost, and you don\'t have a team of high IV Giratina Origin, then Gengar is your next best bet. A high DPS glass cannon with the coveted legacy/event moveset, Gengar makes quick work of this bulky boss.',2),(7,'Mewtwo','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/7/78/150Mewtwo.png',150,'Deoxys (Def)','Confusion/Psycho Cut','Psychic','Shadow Ball','Ghost','An all around great counter if you have the coveted legacy move, Shadow Ball. Mewtwo has the well rounded stats to make it a great generalist and a hard hitter against Deoxys',3),(8,'Weavile','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/d/d2/461Weavile.png',461,'Deoxys (Def)','Feint Attack','Dark','Foul Play','Dark','Weavile is like a less powerful, more bulky Gengar, that happens to be a Dark type. A hard hitter and decent option if you don\'t have access to the aforementioned Legendaries or exclusive-move Gengar',4),(14,'Kyogre','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/4/41/382Kyogre.png',382,'Marowak (Alolan)','Waterfall','Water','Hydro Pump','Water','The King of the Sea makes a triumphant entrance into any battle where the boss is weak to Water.',1),(15,'Giratina (Origin)','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/2/2b/487Giratina-Origin.png',487,'Marowak (Alolan)','Shadow Claw','Ghost','Shadow Ball','Ghost','If it\'s weak to Ghost, your best bet will be Giratina Origin. Shadow Claw/Shadow Ball makes Giratina Origin like a bulky Gengar. It is the supreme Ghost type counter.',3),(16,'Tyranitar','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/8/82/248Tyranitar.png',248,'Marowak (Alolan)','Bite','Dark','Crunch','Dark','An all around generalist that sports two incredible movesets against Alolan Marowak - not listed is Smack Down/Stone Edge, due to the fact that people may not have the exclusive move.',4),(17,'Rampardos','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/8/8a/409Rampardos.png',409,'Marowak (Alolan)','Smack Down','Rock','Rock Slide','Rock','The go-to Rock-type counter, Rampardos is definitely a safe option if you are looking to for low TTW and don\'t care about survivability.',5),(18,'Gyarados','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/4/41/130Gyarados.png',130,'Marowak (Alolan)','Waterfall','Water','Hydro Pump','Water','The budget Kyogre. Use this aquatic menace if you didn\'t secure a Kyogre when it was in rotation',2),(19,'Gyarados','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/4/41/130Gyarados.png',130,'Rhydon','Waterfall','Water','Hydro Pump','Water','The budget Kyogre. Use this aquatic menace if you didn\'t secure a Kyogre when it was in rotation',2),(20,'Kyogre','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/4/41/382Kyogre.png',382,'Rhydon','Waterfall','Water','Hydro Pump','Water','The King of the Sea makes a triumphant entrance into any battle where the boss is weak to Water.',1),(21,'Roserade','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/0/05/407Roserade.png/500px-407Roserade.png',407,'Rhydon','Razor Leaf','Grass','Grass Knot','Grass','With the new inclusion of Grass Knot in Roserade\'s movepool, Roserade has primed itself to be a prominent Grass attacker in the meta',3),(22,'Feraligatr','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/d/d5/160Feraligatr.png',160,'Rhydon','Water Gun','Water','Hydro Cannon','Water','Community Day treated Feraligatr very well. A high DPS attack like Hydro Cannon boosted this baddie way up the ranks',4),(23,'Machamp','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/8/8f/068Machamp.png',68,'Tyranitar','Counter','Fighting','Dynamic Punch','Fighting','Machamp has been the *supreme* Fighting-type counter, and will likely remain that way even with the fighting trio from Unova. Load up your teams with high IV and level Machamp and you\'ll clear out a Tyranitar in no time',1),(24,'Hariyama','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/6/6f/297Hariyama.png',297,'Tyranitar','Counter','Fighting','Dynamic Punch','Fighting','Basically its a budget Machamp with slightly lower damage output. The pair share the same optimal Fighting-type moveset, so feel free to use a mix of the former and the latter',2),(25,'Breloom','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/d/de/286Breloom.png',286,'Tyranitar','Counter','Fighting','Dynamic Punch','Fighting','A versatile but less frequently used counter, Breloom has its potential with its lower overall TTW. A bit more frail, though, so stock up on potions!',3),(26,'Machamp','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/8/8f/068Machamp.png',68,'Aggron','Counter','Fighting','Dynamic Punch','Fighting','Aggron is 4x weak to Fighting. As is Tyranitar. If Machamp is being used as the #1 counter for Tyranitar, you can bet your bottom dollar he\'ll wind up on this list.',1),(27,'Hariyama','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/6/6f/297Hariyama.png',297,'Aggron','Counter','Fighting','Dynamic Punch','Fighting','Budget Machamp makes a return as #2 counter for Aggron. Why? Because he\'s basically Machamp. Thats why.',2),(28,'Groudon','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/7/70/383Groudon.png',383,'Aggron','Mud Shot','Ground','Earthquake','Ground','Groudon is the go to Ground attacker. Aggron is 4x weak to Ground-types. Groudon has the lowest death count out of all counters, and if survivability is your main concern, go with Groudon.',3),(29,'Breloom','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/d/de/286Breloom.png',286,'Aggron','Counter','Fighting','Dynamic Punch','Fighting','A versatile but less frequently used counter, Breloom has its potential with its lower overall TTW. A bit more frail, though, so stock up on potions!',4),(30,'Machamp','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/8/8f/068Machamp.png',68,'Absol','Counter','Fighting','Dynamic Punch','Fighting','Machamp has been the *supreme* Fighting-type counter, and will likely remain that way even with the fighting trio from Unova. Load up your teams with high IV and level Machamp and you\'ll clear out Absol in no time',1),(31,'Hariyama','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/6/6f/297Hariyama.png',297,'Absol','Counter','Fighting','Dynamic Punch','Fighting','Budget Machamp makes a return as #2 counter for Absol. The slightly lower damage output places Hairyama second only to Machamp, but because the two share the same optimal Fighting-type moveset, they can be used interchangeably',2),(32,'Breloom','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/d/de/286Breloom.png',286,'Absol','Counter','Fighting','Dynamic Punch','Fighting','A versatile but less frequently used counter, Breloom has its potential with its lower overall TTW. A bit more frail, though, so stock up on potions!',4),(33,'Toxicroak','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/8/8b/454Toxicroak.png/500px-454Toxicroak.png',454,'Absol','Counter','Fighting','Dynamic Punch','Fighting','Toxicroak is a new addition to the Fighting-type raid meta. Soup to nuts, if it can sport the best Fighting-type moveset, which Toxicroak does, then he\'ll make any Fighting counter list.',4),(34,'Kyogre','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/4/41/382Kyogre.png',382,'Onix','Waterfall','Water','Hydro Pump','Water','The King of the Sea makes a triumphant entrance into any battle where the boss is weak to Water.',1),(35,'Gyarados','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/4/41/130Gyarados.png',130,'Onix','Waterfall','Water','Hydro Pump','Water','The budget Kyogre. Use this aquatic menace if you didn\'t secure a Kyogre when it was in rotation',2),(36,'Roserade','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/0/05/407Roserade.png/500px-407Roserade.png',407,'Onix','Razor Leaf','Grass','Grass Knot','Grass','With the new inclusion of Grass Knot in Roserade\'s movepool, Roserade has primed itself to be a prominent Grass attacker in the meta',3),(37,'Feraligatr','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/d/d5/160Feraligatr.png',160,'Onix','Water Gun','Water','Hydro Cannon','Water','Community Day treated Feraligatr very well. A high DPS attack like Hydro Cannon boosted this baddie way up the ranks',4),(38,'Metagross','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/0/05/376Metagross.png/500px-376Metagross.png',376,'Aerodactyl','Bullet Punch','Steel','Meteor Mash','Steel','Metagross is the... meta... for steel types. His Community Day move, Meteor Mash, is a must have to use against bosses weak to Steel-types.',1),(39,'Kyogre','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/4/41/382Kyogre.png',382,'Aerodactyl','Waterfall','Water','Hydro Pump','Water','If it\'s weak to Water, Kyogre will almost always be in the top counters without a doubt.',2),(41,'Electivire','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/2/23/466Electivire.png',466,'Aerodactyl','Thunder Shock','Electric','Wild Charge','Electric','The reason why Electivire is taking the #3 spot and not Raikou or Zapdos is because Electivire and Raikou are about equal in power, but Raikou is harder to obtain, being a legendary. Additionally, Zapdos is weak to Rock-types, which Aerodactyl is, and therefore poses a graver threat to Zapdos than Electivire',3),(42,'Dialga','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/8/8a/483Dialga.png',483,'Aerodactyl','Metal Claw','Steel','Iron Head','Steel','Dialga is like Metagross, though with a slightly lower bulk so its TTW is just a tad higher. Go with a dual Steel-type moveset to take on Aerodactyl',4),(43,'Rampardos','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/8/8a/409Rampardos.png/500px-409Rampardos.png',409,'Aerodactyl','Smack Down','Rock','Rock Slide','Rock','Rampardos has dethroned the previous king of Rock-types: Tyranitar. Boasting an attack stat that rivals Mewtwo, this Rock-type beast is sure to slay any boss that dares stand in its way.',5),(44,'Metagross','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/0/05/376Metagross.png/500px-376Metagross.png',376,'Shuckle','Bullet Punch','Steel','Meteor Mash','Steel','Despite being the #1 counter for Shuckle, Metagross takes an awful long time to kill this stubborn turtle. It\'s a gentle reminder that one simply cannot fuckle with the Shuckle',1),(45,'Dialga','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/8/8a/483Dialga.png',483,'Shuckle','Metal Claw','Steel','Iron Head','Steel','Even Dialga, the God of Time, cannot crush this puny, rocky bug turtle. That says something about Shuckle. He\'s even more powerful than the poke-gods.',2),(46,'Kyogre','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/4/41/382Kyogre.png',382,'Shuckle','Waterfall','Water','Hydro Pump','Water','The King of the Sea makes a triumphant entrance into any battle where the boss is weak to Water. And Shuckle laughed.',3),(47,'Rampardos','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/8/8a/409Rampardos.png/500px-409Rampardos.png',409,'Shuckle','Smack Down','Rock','Rock Slide','Rock','Ok, now we\'re just getting ridiculous. If the gods of time and the sea can\'t take down a turtle, why do you think an ancient rock dinosaur can?',4),(48,'Metagross','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/0/05/376Metagross.png/500px-376Metagross.png',376,'Lunatone','Bullet Punch','Steel','Meteor Mash','Steel','Metagross is the... meta... for steel types. His Community Day move, Meteor Mash, is a must have to use against bosses weak to Steel-types.',1),(49,'Dialga','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/8/8a/483Dialga.png',483,'Lunatone','Metal Claw','Steel','Iron Head','Steel','Dialga is a safe bet for battling Lunatone, sporting high attack and powerful Steel type moveset, as well as a resistance to Psychic types',2),(50,'Kyogre','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/4/41/382Kyogre.png',382,'Lunatone','Waterfall','Water','Hydro Pump','Water','If it\'s weak to Water, Kyogre will almost always be in the top counters without a doubt.',3),(51,'Giratina (Origin)','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/2/2b/487Giratina-Origin.png',487,'Lunatone','Shadow Claw','Ghost','Shadow Ball','Ghost','If it\'s weak to Ghost, your best bet will be Giratina Origin. Shadow Claw/Shadow Ball makes Giratina Origin like a bulky Gengar. It is the supreme Ghost type counter.',4),(52,'Gengar','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/c/c6/094Gengar.png',94,'Lunatone','Shadow Claw/Lick','Ghost','Shadow Ball','Ghost','Only use Gengar if you have the coveted fast move Shadow Claw, or its Raid Day exclusive move Lick. Giratina Origin is a much better Ghost type attacker',5),(53,'Metagross','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/0/05/376Metagross.png/500px-376Metagross.png',376,'Solrock','Bullet Punch','Steel','Meteor Mash','Steel','Metagross is the... meta... for steel types. His Community Day move, Meteor Mash, is a must have to use against bosses weak to Steel-types.',1),(54,'Dialga','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/8/8a/483Dialga.png',483,'Solrock','Metal Claw','Steel','Iron Head','Steel','Dialga is a safe bet for battling Solrock, sporting high attack and powerful Steel type moveset, as well as a resistance to Solrock\'s Solar Beam',2),(55,'Giratina (Origin)','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/2/2b/487Giratina-Origin.png',487,'Solrock','Shadow Claw','Ghost','Shadow Ball','Ghost','Giratina Origin takes the #3 spot instead of Kyogre simply because Solrock has access to Solar Beam. Know what moveset you\'re going up against when choosing counters. However, as repeated before, if it\'s weak to Ghost, your best bet will be Giratina Origin. Shadow Claw/Shadow Ball makes Giratina Origin like a bulky Gengar. It is the supreme Ghost type counter.',3),(56,'Kyogre','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/4/41/382Kyogre.png',382,'Solrock','Waterfall','Water','Hydro Pump','Water','When Solrock doesn\'t have Solar Beam as it\'s raid battle move, feel free to use the King of the Sea, Kyogre.',4),(57,'Tyranitar','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/8/82/248Tyranitar.png',248,'Solrock','Bite','Dark','Crunch','Dark','Tyranitar really serves most of its purpose these days as a Dark-type generalist. Solrock is weak to Dark, so use Tyranitar when you don\'t really have other options.',4),(58,'Tyranitar','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/8/82/248Tyranitar.png',248,'Deoxys (Def)','Bite','Dark','Crunch','Dark','Tyranitar really serves most of its purpose these days as a Dark-type generalist. Deoxys is weak to Dark, so use Tyranitar when you don\'t really have other options. He can be used \r\ninterchangeably with Weavile.',5),(59,'Tyranitar','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/8/82/248Tyranitar.png',248,'Cresselia','Bite','Dark','Crunch','Dark','Tyranitar really serves most of its purpose these days as a Dark-type generalist. Cresselia is weak to Dark, so use Tyranitar when you don\'t really have other options. He can be used interchangeably with Weavile.',4),(60,'Scizor','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/5/55/212Scizor.png/500px-212Scizor.png',212,'Cresselia','Fury Cutter','Bug','X-Scissor','Bug','Scizor is the best all around Bug-type attacker right now. If you have a lot of people in your raid lobby, and TTW is not of concern, it\'s safe to use Scizor. There are better counters, so just keep that in mind.',5),(62,'Raikou','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/c/c1/243Raikou.png/1200px-243Raikou.png',243,'Kygore','Thunder Shock','Electric','Wild Charge','Electric','Raikou is hands down the #1 attacker against anything Water-type. Kyogre has access to Blizzard, which makes Raikou better than its Gen 1 legendary counterpart, Zapdos. It also has a much lower TTW than most other counters',1),(72,'Electivire','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/2/23/466Electivire.png',466,'Kygore','Thunder Shock','Electric','Wild Charge','Electric','Electivire is like the non-legendary Raikou. It shares the same optimal moveset and boasts a similar TTW, though is less bulky and will likely faint more often unless you\'re in a larger group. Use Electivire if you don\'t have a team of high IV/CP Raikou.',2),(82,'Magnezone','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/5/53/462Magnezone.png',462,'Kygore','Spark','Electric','Wild Charge','Electric','Magnezone shares a similar attack stat to Raikou, and is much bulkier than its legendary dog counterpart. However, Spark is nowhere near as efficient of a Fast Move as Thunder Shock, which Magnezone unfortunately does not have access to yet. For this reason, Magnezone\'s TTW is significantly lower, however using Magnezone in large groups where TTW doesn\'t matter shouldn\'t be too much of an issue.',3),(92,'Sceptile','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/3/3e/254Sceptile.png/250px-254Sceptile.png',254,'Kygore','Fury Cutter','Bug','Frenzy Plant','Grass','Sceptile starts the Grass-counters. Grass-types, while useful against Kyogre, have a significant disadvantage due to Kyogre\'s access to Blizzard. Know what moveset you\'re facing before you rush in with a Grass team. Regardless, let\'s talk Fury Cutter: Fury Cutter is such a beast of a Bug-type move that, when paired with Frenzy Plant, its TTFA (Time to Full Activation) is just 3.4 seconds! Compare this with Venusaur\'s considerably slower 5.4 seconds. That\'s a considerable charge-up difference, which is why Venusaur isn\'t even making this list.',4),(102,'Roserade','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/0/05/407Roserade.png/250px-407Roserade.png',407,'Kygore','Razor Leaf','Grass','Grass Knot','Grass','Similar to Sceptile, Roserade is at a significant disadvantage against Blizzard. That said, Roserade resists Kyogre\'s electric and water attacks, making it a viable counter in these scenarios. Roserade\'s Razor Leaf is nowhere near as efficient as Vine Whip or Fury Cutter charging up a Frenzy Plant though. It\'s TTFA is around 8 seconds, so keep this in mind as you enter a raid battle with it.',5),(112,'Exeggutor (Alolan)','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/7/74/103Exeggutor-Alola.png',103,'Kygore','Bullet Seed','Grass','Solar Beam','Grass','Alolan Exeggutor has one of the weaker Grass movesets, however, its stats make up for its lack of powerful moves. Sporting significantly higher stats than Venusaur, Alolan Exeggutor\'s TTW and lower death count manage to place it higher than the former.',6),(122,'Moltres','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/1/1b/146Moltres.png/1200px-146Moltres.png',146,'Venusaur','Fire Spin','Fire','Sky Attack','Flying','Moltres is easily the most versatile Fire type attacker in the game at this stage, given its access to powerful Fire and Flying type moves. If you missed Moltres Day and didn\'t get a Sky Attack Moltres, Overheat also pairs quite nicely with this Legendary Bird',1),(132,'Heatran','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/b/b7/485Heatran.png',485,'Venusaur','Fire Spin','Fire','Fire Blast','Fire','An under-utilized but still quite effective Fire attacker, Heatran is the go to potion conservationist of any Fire-type attacking team. Its high bulk allows it to tank even the toughest attacks, plus its Steel dual typing allows it to resist Venusaur\'s poison attacks. Heatran has the lowest faint count of all counters, but it is hindered by Fire Blast, which is not as powerful or as energy efficient as Overheat.',2),(142,'Mewtwo','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/7/78/150Mewtwo.png',150,'Venusaur','Psycho Cut/Confusion','Psychic','Psychic','Psychic','The Pokemon demigod returns, again, as a versatile generalist. Venusaur, being weak to Psychic attacks, is easily torn apart by Mewtwo. Mewtwo has a powerful moveset that allows it to sport a similar TTW as Moltres (385.1s vs 376.8s). Feel free to toss a few Mewtwo into the mix when you face off against Venusaur',3),(152,'Entei','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/f/f9/244Entei.png',244,'Venusaur','Fire Spin','Fire','Overheat','Fire','Entei is effectively the budget Moltres. It has a lower attack stat but similar bulk. However, Moltres\' access to Sky Attack allows the TTFA for its charged moves is more than HALF of Entei\'s TTFA for Overheat. For this reason, Overheat Moltres and Overheat Entei are used almost interchangeably.',4),(162,'Mewtwo','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/7/78/150Mewtwo.png',150,'Raichu (Alolan)','Psycho Cut/Confusion','Psychic','Shadow Ball','Ghost','The ultimate generalist, Mewtwo counters Alolan Raichu with its access to Shadow Ball, and is only boosted by its uber-high attack. Its low faint count makes it a supreme counter, and takes the #1 spot',2),(172,'Giratina (Origin)','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/2/2b/487Giratina-Origin.png',487,'Raichu (Alolan)','Shadow Claw','Ghost','Shadow Ball','Ghost','If it\'s weak to Ghost, your best bet will be Giratina Origin. Shadow Claw/Shadow Ball makes Giratina Origin like a bulky Gengar. It is the supreme Ghost type counter.',1),(192,'Tyranitar','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/8/82/248Tyranitar.png',248,'Raichu (Alolan)','Bite','Dark','Crunch','Dark','As of late, Tyranitar has been re-positioned in the meta and serves more as a Dark-type generalist. Bite/Crunch is the best Dark-type moveset, and combined with his high stats, Tyranitar has an extremely high TTW and low death count',3),(212,'Groudon','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/7/70/383Groudon.png',383,'Raichu (Alolan)','Mud Shot','Ground','Earthquake','Ground','Groudon is an absolute TANK. He\'s also the go-to Ground-type attacker, next to Garchomp. However, few players have Garchomp yet. The two counters can be used almost interchangeably due to their access to the optimal Ground-type moveset',4),(222,'Garchomp','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/f/fa/445Garchomp.png',445,'Jolteon','Mud Shot','Ground','Earthquake','Ground','Garchomp is the pseudo-legendary version of Groudon. He sports the best offensive Ground-type moveset, and carries an incredible base Stamina stat of 239! This Dragon-Ground beast can dish out far more damage before fainting due to its speed, and therefore earns the #1 spot on this list',1),(232,'Groudon','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/7/70/383Groudon.png',383,'Jolteon','Mud Shot','Ground','Earthquake','Ground','While definitely the tankiest option, Groudon is outclassed by Garchomp in terms of speed. The pair\'s TTW is almost identical though, so if you don\'t have a Garchomp or two to spare, go with Groudon, as the results will be practically the same',2),(242,'Rhyperior','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/d/d9/464Rhyperior.png/250px-464Rhyperior.png',464,'Jolteon','Mud-Slap','Ground','Earthquake','Ground','Rhyperior is like the budget Groudon. Slightly lower in every base state category (except stamina), and does not have access to the best Ground-type moveset. Mud-Slap is not as energy efficient and doesn\'t charge up Earthquake as fast as Mud Shot. However, Rhyperior and Groudon have the same faint count, so go with Rhyperior if you don\'t have enough Groudon to fill a team.',3),(252,'Mamoswine','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/d/d0/473Mamoswine.png/1200px-473Mamoswine.png',473,'Jolteon','Mud-Slap','Ground','Bulldoze','Ground','Mamoswine is renowned for its versatility as an Ice-type attacker, however, it does serve a purpose as a budget Ground-type attacker. That is, however, if you have the Sinnoh Stones to spare evolving a bunch of Mamoswine. We don\'t recommend using this counter, despite it being so high up in the counter matchup. Mamoswine doesn\'t have anywhere near the ideal Ground-type moveset. Bulldoze just doesn\'t deal as much damage as Earthquake. You would be better off using the above counters instead.',4),(262,'Mewtwo','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/7/78/150Mewtwo.png',150,'Machamp','Confusion','Psychic','Psychic','Psychic','Who else but Mewtwo? Of course, if something is weak to Psychic, you can expect Mewtwo to take the #1 spot. Boasting incredible stats and the moveset to back it up, Mewtwo makes for the ideal generalist.',1),(272,'Alakazam','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/c/cc/065Alakazam.png',65,'Machamp','Confusion','Psychic','Future Sight','Psychic','A budget Mewtwo with a lower TTW and higher death count due to its fragility. Alakazam is still a very versatile Psychic-type counter',2),(282,'Azelf','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/d/d0/482Azelf.png',482,'Machamp','Confusion','Psychic','Future Sight','Psychic','Honestly, when I saw this Lake Pixie show up as the #3 counter on Pokebattler for most simulations, I was incredibly surprised. However, it\'s understandable considering Azelf\'s notoriously high Attack stat. Its TTW rivals that of Mewtwo, despite its lack of bulk.',3),(292,'Rayquaza','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/e/e4/384Rayquaza.png/1200px-384Rayquaza.png',384,'Machamp','Air Slash','Flying','Aerial Ace','Flying','Rayquaza is unique, for the reason that it is a contender for #1 Flying-type AND Dragon-type attacker. It stands to reason that Rayquaza would make this list. Rayquaza also takes reduced damage from Fighting-type moves.<br/><br/>Other potential Flying-type candidates include Sky Attack Moltres, Honchkrow, and Lugia. However, due to Machamp\'s access to Rock Slide, it is not recommended that you go with any Flying-type counters, even Rayquaza. Only choose Flying-attackers if you know for sure Machamp does not have Rock Slide!',4),(312,'Garchomp','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/f/fa/445Garchomp.png',445,'Raikou','Mud Shot','Ground','Earthquake','Ground','Garchomp is the pseudo-legendary version of Groudon. He sports the best offensive <span class =‘Ground’>Ground</span>-type moveset, and an incredible base Stamina! It also helps that Garchomp doubly-resists Raikou’s <span class=‘Electric>Electric</span>-type attacks with it’s dual <span class=‘Dragon’>Dragon</span>/<span class =‘Ground’>Ground</span> typing. This beast can dish out far more damage before fainting due to its speed,  therefore earns the #1 spot on this list',1),(322,'Groudon','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/7/70/383Groudon.png',383,'Raikou','Mud Shot','Ground','Earthquake','Ground','While definitely the tankiest option, Groudon is outclassed by Garchomp in terms of speed. The pair\'s TTW is almost identical though, so if you don\'t have a Garchomp or two to spare, go with Groudon, as the results will be practically the same',2),(332,'Rhyperior','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/d/d9/464Rhyperior.png/250px-464Rhyperior.png',464,'Raikou','Mud-Slap','Ground','Earthquake','Ground','Rhyperior is like the budget Groudon. Slightly lower in every base state category (except stamina), and does not have access to the best Ground-type moveset. Mud-Slap is not as energy efficient and doesn\'t charge up Earthquake as fast as Mud Shot. However, Rhyperior and Groudon have the same faint count, so go with Rhyperior if you don\'t have enough Groudon to fill a team.',3),(342,'Mamoswine','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/d/d0/473Mamoswine.png/1200px-473Mamoswine.png',473,'Raikou','Mud-Slap','Ground','Bulldoze','Ground','Mamoswine is renowned for its versatility as an Ice-type attacker, however, it does serve a purpose as a budget Ground-type attacker. That is, however, if you have the Sinnoh Stones to spare evolving a bunch of Mamoswine. We don\'t recommend using this counter, despite it being so high up in the counter matchup. Mamoswine doesn\'t have anywhere near the ideal Ground-type moveset. Bulldoze just doesn\'t deal as much damage as Earthquake. You would be better off using the above counters instead.',4),(352,'Donphan','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/5/53/232Donphan.png',232,'Raikou','Mud-Slap','Ground','Earthquake','Ground','Donphan gets a time to shine now that Mud-Slap has been added to its move pool! However, TTW rises significantly, so be wary of using it!',5),(362,'Nidoking','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/c/c6/034Nidoking.png',34,'Raikou','Fury Cutter','Bug','Earth Power','Ground','Since the introduction of Earth Power, Nidoking became much more viable as a Ground-type attacker. Itâ€™s not great, but it makes a good replacement if you donâ€™t have one of the above counters.',6),(372,'Gyarados','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/4/41/130Gyarados.png',130,'Groudon','Waterfall','Water','Hydro Pump','Water','Gyarados, surprisingly, takes the #1 position away from Kyogre. Gyarados\' unique typing allows it to resist Groudon\'s powerful Solar Beam attacks. However, just because Gyarados isn\'t legendary doesn\'t mean you\'re compromising on power. The two share similar attack stats, so you can guarantee Gyarados will get the job done!',1),(382,'Palkia','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/6/66/484Palkia.png',484,'Groudon','Dragon Tail','Dragon','Hydro Pump','Water','Palkia was added to the game after Groudon\'s latest return in mid January 2019 for the Hoenn Celebration. Since its addition, Palkia actually now outperforms Kyogre as the best Water-type legendary, at least against Groudon. Thanks to its unique Dragon/Water typing, Palkia doubly resists Fire Blast and takes neutral damage from Solar Beam. Watch out for Groudon\'s Dragon Tail though, as Palkia still takes SE damage from it.',2),(392,'Mewtwo','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/7/78/150Mewtwo.png',150,'Groudon','Psycho Cut','Psychic','Ice Beam','Ice','Mewtwo is the prime, versatile generalist. It can tank Groudon\'s moves in any weather situation and deals SE damage with Ice Beam. Usually, we recommend either Confusion or Psycho Cut, but since dealing the most SE damage is desired, use Psycho Cut - it charges Mewtwo\'s Ice Beam far faster than Confusion',3),(402,'Kyogre','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/4/41/382Kyogre.png',382,'Groudon','Waterfall','Water','Hydro Pump','Water','Kyogre is severely hindered by Groudon\'s Solar Beam. Kyogre remains a top counter in nearly every situation, but when faced with SB Groudon, it tears through Kyogre like it\'s cotton candy. Use Kyogre if and only if you know the moveset you\'re facing.',4),(412,'Glaceon','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/2/23/471Glaceon.png',471,'Groudon','Frost Breath','Ice','Avalanche','Ice','We decided to give Glaceon a chance to shine, and represent the Ice type counters. Ice types don\'t fare so well against Groudon\'s Fire Blast. Use Ice types, like Glaceon and Mamoswine, with utmost caution.',6),(422,'Feraligatr','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/d/d5/160Feraligatr.png',160,'Groudon','Water Gun','Water','Hydro Cannon','Water','Community Day treated Feraligatr very well. It made Feraligatr a super-powerful Water-type. User beware! Only use Feraligatr if Groudon is not packing Solar Beam.',5),(432,'Rampardos','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/8/8a/409Rampardos.png',409,'Scyther','Smack Down','Rock','Rock Slide','Rock','Rampardos is the new Rock-type king. With a beefy 295 attack, Rampardos tears through Scyther like itâ€™s nothing, and in record time! The average TTW according to Pokebattler is 76.6 seconds!',1),(442,'Tyranitar','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/8/82/248Tyranitar.png',248,'Scyther','Smack Down','Rock','Stone Edge','Rock','Community Day might have treated our favorite generalist quite nicely, however Tyranitar has been dethroned as the Rock-type #1. Taking a back seat to the Rock-type meta game, Tyranitar still sports an impressive TTW of 93.8 seconds. Since Cranidos are hard to come by, thereâ€™s a good chance a few SD Tyranitar wind up on your team.',2),(452,'Rhyperior','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/d/d9/464Rhyperior.png',464,'Scyther','Smack Down','Rock','Stone Edge','Rock','Rhyperior has all around good stats and a solid movepool to back up its Rock and Ground typing. Using SD/SE with Rhyperior will reward you with a defeated Scyther, at the expense of the timer. Rhyperior is just a bit slower than Tyranitar.',3),(462,'Regirock','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/a/aa/377Regirock.png',377,'Scyther','Rock Throw','Rock','Stone Edge','Rock','Regirock is definitely the Legendary go-to for Scyther raids, considering its double weakness to Rock. This is why the other Legendary options (Rayquaza, Heatran, and Moltres) arenâ€™t being shown. However, TTW significantly rises (124.4 sec) with Regirock, since the legendary golemâ€™s stats arenâ€™t too spectacular.',4),(472,'Giratina (Origin)','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/2/2b/487Giratina-Origin.png',487,'Starmie','Shadow Claw','Ghost','Shadow Ball','Ghost','Starmie\'s most ideal counters are powerful Ghost and Electric types. Giratina Origin form offers the best bang for your buck: Low TTW and low faint count. Make sure this meta-dominating Ghost-type attacker is at the top of your roster',1),(482,'Raikou','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/c/c1/243Raikou.png/1200px-243Raikou.png',243,'Starmie','Thunder Shock','Electric','Wild Charge','Electric','Raikou is hands down one of the best attackers against anything Water-type. Make some good use of the Raikou you obtained during its respective Raid Day and solo a few Starmie raids!',2),(492,'Magnezone','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/5/53/462Magnezone.png',462,'Starmie','Spark','Electric','Wild Charge','Electric','Magnezone shares a similar attack stat to Raikou, and is much bulkier than its legendary dog counterpart. However, Spark is nowhere near as efficient of a Fast Move as Thunder Shock, which Magnezone unfortunately does not have access to yet. For this reason, Magnezone\'s TTW is significantly lower, however using Magnezone in large groups where TTW doesn\'t matter shouldn\'t be too much of an issue.',3),(502,'Electivire','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/2/23/466Electivire.png',466,'Starmie','Thunder Shock','Electric','Wild Charge','Electric','Electivire is like the non-legendary Raikou. It shares the same optimal moveset and boasts a similar TTW, though is less bulky and will likely faint more often unless you\'re in a larger group. Use Electivire if you don\'t have a team of high IV/CP Raikou.',4),(512,'Blaziken','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/9/90/257Blaziken.png',257,'Tyranitar','Counter','Fighting','Focus Blast','Fighting','Blaziken outcompetes its primate Fire-Fighting cousin, Infernape, by a long shot when it comes to viability as a raider. Not only does it have all around higher stats, but it also has access to Counter, one of the best Fighting type fast moves. The TTFA is significantly less desirable than Blaziken\'s fellow Fighting types, however. Regardless, Blaziken deserves its recognition as a viable Tyranitar counter.',4),(522,'Blaziken','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/9/90/257Blaziken.png',257,'Absol','Counter','Fighting','Focus Blast','Fighting','Blaziken outcompetes its primate Fire-Fighting cousin, Infernape, by a long shot when it comes to viability as a raider. Not only does it have all around higher stats, but it also has access to Counter, one of the best Fighting type fast moves. The TTFA is significantly less desirable than Blaziken\'s fellow Fighting types, however. Regardless, Blaziken deserves its recognition as a viable Absol counter.',5),(532,'Toxicroak','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/8/8b/454Toxicroak.png/500px-454Toxicroak.png',454,'Tyranitar','Counter','Fighting','Dynamic Punch','Fighting','Toxicroak is a new addition to the Fighting-type raid meta. Soup to nuts, if it can sport the best Fighting-type moveset, which Toxicroak does, then he\'ll make any Fighting counter list. Toxicroak can be used interchangeably with other less powerful/higher TTW counters, since raiding in larger groups shouldn\'t impact overall victory.',5),(542,'Raikou','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/thumb/c/c1/243Raikou.png/1200px-243Raikou.png',243,'Lapras','Thunder Shock','Electric','Wild Charge','Electric','Raikou is the #1 attacker against anything Water-type. Kyogre has access to Blizzard, which makes Raikou better than its Gen 1 legendary counterpart, Zapdos. It also has a much lower TTW than most other counters',1),(552,'Magnezone','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/5/53/462Magnezone.png',462,'Lapras','Spark','Electric','Wild Charge','Electric','Magnezone shares a similar attack stat to Raikou, and is much bulkier than its legendary dog counterpart. However, Spark is nowhere near as efficient of a Fast Move as Thunder Shock, which Magnezone unfortunately does not have access to yet. For this reason, Magnezone\'s TTW is significantly lower, however using Magnezone in large groups where TTW doesn\'t matter shouldn\'t be too much of an issue.',2),(562,'Electivire','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/2/23/466Electivire.png',466,'Lapras','Thunder Shock','Electric','Wild Charge','Electric','Electivire is like the non-legendary Raikou. It shares the same optimal moveset and boasts a similar TTW, though is less bulky and will likely faint more often unless you\'re in a larger group. Use Electivire if you don\'t have a team of high IV/CP Raikou.',3),(572,'Machamp','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/8/8f/068Machamp.png',68,'Lapras','Counter','Fighting','Dynamic Punch','Fighting','If it\'s weak to Fighting, Machamp will rise to the occasion. Lapras is weak to Fighting-type moves, and does not have any threatening moves to counter Machamp. However, the Electric-attackers have lower TTW, so use Machamp sparingly here.',4),(582,'Zapdos','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/e/e3/145Zapdos.png',145,'Lapras','Thunder Shock','Electric','Thunderbolt','Electric','Zapdos finally makes it onto a counter chart! This is mainly because Electric-types happen to fare a bit better than Fighting-types (aside from Machamp) against Lapras. However, use Zapdos sparingly. Lapras is known for its deadly Ice-type movesets, which could take down Zapdos easily if you aren\'t prepared to dodge!',5),(592,'Yanmega','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/e/e6/469Yanmega.png',469,'Shiftry','Bug Bite','Bug','Bug Buzz','Bug','Take advantage of Shiftry\'s double weakness to Bug-types, trainers! Yanmega finally has its time to shine - this powerful Bug beast packs a punch! Yanmega has one of the lowest overall TTW against Shiftry + it has among the lowest death count.',1),(602,'Pinsir','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/7/71/127Pinsir.png',127,'Shiftry','Bug Bite','Bug','X-Scissor','Bug','Pinsir has been a reliable Bug-type attacker from the get go. Its slightly higher attack and defense stats allow it to put out more damage, lending it to have the lowest TTW out of all counters! However, Pinsir lacks Yanmega\'s stamina, so faint count is a bit higher.',2),(612,'Scizor','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/5/55/212Scizor.png',212,'Shiftry','Fury Cutter','Bug','X-Scissor','Bug','Scizor is one of the best all around Bug-type attackers. It has slightly higher stats than Yanmega, but Fury Cutter lends it to have a slightly higher TTW. However, those higher stats do help Scizor out with survivability. Out of every counter, Scizor has the lowest faint count!',3),(622,'Heatran','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/b/b7/485Heatran.png',485,'Shiftry','Bug Bite','Bug','Fire Blast','Fire','Heatran is unique, in that it can serve as a Bug-type attacker despite being a Fire/Steel type. Nonetheless, Heatran sports two devastating moves against Shiftry. However, despite having significantly higher stats than its rivaling Bug-type counters, Heatran lacks an optimal moveset, and only gets STAB on its Charged attack. As a result, Heatran has a very high TTW, and should only be used when TTW is not a concern.',4),(632,'Moltres','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/1/1b/146Moltres.png',146,'Shiftry','Fire Spin','Fire','Sky Attack','Flying','Moltres, despite packing the best Flying-type move AND being a beastly Fire-type attacker, takes a back seat to the Shiftry raids. This is primarily because other counters are able to take advantage of Shiftry\'s double weakness to Bug. Moltres might get STAB on both of its attacks (and Overheat can be used in place of Sky Attack), but the damage output isn\'t enough to make Moltres rival Yanmega or Scizor in this scenario',5),(642,'Moltres','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/1/1b/146Moltres.png',146,'Tangela','Fire Spin','Fire','Sky Attack','Flying','You can basically assume that if something is weak to Fire, Moltres will find its way onto the counter list. Use Overheat interchangeably with Sky Attack.',1),(652,'Heatran','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/b/b7/485Heatran.png',485,'Tangela','Fire Spin','Fire','Fire Blast','Fire','Despite not having the most ideal moveset, making its TTW suffer slightly, Heatran still finds itself at the #2 counter spot for Tangela. Its stats are phenomenal, and its high bulk allows Heatran to have maximal survivability, averaging only two faints during a raid!',2),(662,'Entei','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/f/f9/244Entei.png',244,'Tangela','Fire Spin','Fire','Overheat','Fire','Entei is a tanky Fire-type attacker, sporting the optimal Fire-type moveset of Fire Spin and Overheat (well, next to Blast Burn). Entei\'s TDO is outclassed by Moltres with Sky Attack, though. Regardless, Entei makes for a great counter and should be used on your team if you have a good Entei to spare.',3),(672,'Charizard','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/7/7e/006Charizard.png',6,'Tangela','Fire Spin','Fire','Blast Burn','Fire','Community Day was a blessing for Charizard. Blast Burn is the best Fire type move currently available, so Charizard is definitely a worthy member of your team. When equipped with Blast Burn, it gets put on par with Entei - a powerful attacker with the stamina to keep it in battle for a while.',4),(832,'Giratina (Origin)','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/2/2b/487Giratina-Origin.png',487,'Deoxys (Speed)','Shadow Claw','Ghost','Shadow Ball','Ghost','If it\'s weak to Ghost, your best bet will be Giratina Origin. Shadow Claw/Shadow Ball makes Giratina Origin like a bulky Gengar. It is the supreme Ghost type counter.',1),(842,'Gengar','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/c/c6/094Gengar.png',94,'Deoxys (Speed)','Shadow Claw/Lick','Ghost','Shadow Ball','Ghost','If it\'s weak to Ghost, and you don\'t have a team of high IV Giratina Origin, then Gengar is your next best bet. A high DPS glass cannon with the coveted legacy/event moveset, Gengar makes quick work of Deoxys.',2),(852,'Mewtwo','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/7/78/150Mewtwo.png',150,'Deoxys (Speed)','Confusion/Psycho Cut','Psychic','Shadow Ball','Ghost','An all around great counter if you have the coveted legacy move, Shadow Ball. Mewtwo has the well rounded stats to make it a great generalist and a hard hitter against Deoxys',3),(862,'Weavile','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/d/d2/461Weavile.png',461,'Deoxys (Speed)','Feint Attack','Dark','Foul Play','Dark','Weavile is like a less powerful, more bulky Gengar, that happens to be a Dark type. A hard hitter and decent option if you don\'t have access to the aforementioned Legendaries or exclusive-move Gengar',5),(872,'Tyranitar','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/8/82/248Tyranitar.png',248,'Deoxys (Speed)','Bite','Dark','Crunch','Dark','It has been well established that Tyranitar is better off used as a Dark-type counter than a Rock-type. Tyranitar might be outclassed by the likes of Giratina Origin, but Bite/Crunch is still a powerful moveset. Plus, with Tyranitar\'s impeccable stats, it should be a prominent fixture on any Deoxys team.',4),(882,'Honchkrow','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/4/46/430Honchkrow.png',430,'Deoxys (Speed)','Snarl','Dark','Dark Pulse','Dark','Honchkrow might not be as strong as Weavile, however, it still manages to outdo normal mainstays like Absol and Houndoom. Be careful when using Honchkrow, though, as it is remarkably frail.',6),(892,'Kyogre','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/4/41/382Kyogre.png',382,'Entei','Waterfall','Water','Hydro Pump','Water','If it\'s weak to Water, Kyogre will almost always be in the top counters without a doubt.',1),(902,'Rampardos','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/8/8a/409Rampardos.png',409,'Entei','Smack Down','Rock','Rock Slide','Rock','Rampardos is the new Rock-type king. With a beefy 295 attack, Rampardos tears through Entei like itâ€™s nothing, and in record time!',2),(952,'Feraligatr','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/d/d5/160Feraligatr.png',160,'Entei','Water Gun','Water','Hydro Cannon','Water','Community Day treated Feraligatr very well. It made Feraligatr a super-powerful Water-type. Entei doesn\'t have any moves that could harm Feraligatr, so use Feraligatr liberally!',3),(962,'Palkia','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/6/66/484Palkia.png',484,'Entei','Dragon Tail','Dragon','Hydro Pump','Water','Palkia is a unique Legendary, in that it has a typing that lets it doubly resist Fire attacks. However, Palkia only outperforms Kyogre in instances where Kyogre\'s opponent sports Grass or Electric moves. Here, Kyogre easily passes Palkia in terms of TDO and TTW. Use Palkia purely as a potion conservationist',4),(972,'Gyarados','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/4/41/130Gyarados.png',130,'Entei','Waterfall','Water','Hydro Pump','Water','The budget Kyogre. Use this aquatic menace if you didn\'t secure a Kyogre when it was in rotation',5),(982,'Tyranitar','https://cdn.bulbagarden.net/upload/8/82/248Tyranitar.png',248,'Entei','Smack Down','Rock','Stone Edge','Rock','Tyranitar functions like a slower Rampardos with a worse charge move. Regardless, Smack Down is a supreme Rock-type fast move, and if you don\'t have Rampardos yet, use Tyranitar.',6);
